Benue State Governor Samuel Ortom has said former President Olusegun Obasanjo had assured him that despite the burning of his mango farm at Howe in Gwer Local Government Area of the state, he will not relocate it to another place. Ortom announced this yesterday in Makurdi, the state capital, during a church service on the 46 years of the creation of the state.   Ousted directors ask for accounts     Tomori decries widespread graft, immorality     Sule releases N340m for retirees’ gratuity   The governor said Obasanjo had planned to build a mango processing factory near the farm. “The mangoes will not be taken to any other place for processing but will be processed in that same place,” he said. Ortom regretted that the people working on the farm would be thrown into the labour market, following the fire that occurred there last weekend. He announced that three of the suspected arsonists had been arrested while others are on the run.